\layout Chapter*

High resolution subdivision schemes
\layout Section

Definitions
\layout Standard

In this paper, we want to show how the subdivision scheme framework can
 be extended by hybrid schemes: mixing tetradic and dyadic subdivision schemes
 for example.
 Given some data 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{j-1,k}\right\} _{k\in \Z }$
\end_inset 

 to interpolate on the dyadic 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j-1,k}$
\end_inset 

 grid, we first apply a dyadic subdivision scheme as an initialisation step:
 since high resolution subdivision schemes can be seen as multistep subdivision
 schemes, it is not surprising that they require an initialisation step.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point high resolution subdivision scheme, a sensible choice for the initializati
on step is the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc dyadic scheme (see lemma 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{lemmecubic}

\end_inset 

) which will copy the data at even nodes (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}=y_{j-1,k}$
\end_inset 

) and insert new values at odd nodes (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k+1}$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

).
 A value 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

stable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}=y_{j+1,2k}$
\end_inset 

, other nodes are said to be temporary or are referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

placeholders
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 A high resolution scheme on a dyadic grid is said to be interpolatory if
 all 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

 values on even nodes (
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

) are stable.
 Assuming we used an interpolatory subdivision scheme as an initialization
 step, the following algorithm is interpolatory.
\layout Algorithm


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

(
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Dyadic High Resolution Subdivision Scheme) The following iteration
 steps depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha $
\end_inset 

, a constant parameter.
 For a given integer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

, begin with some initial 
\begin_inset Formula $y-$
\end_inset 

values 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}\, k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 over dyadic numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j,k}=k/2^{j}$
\end_inset 

 where only the even nodes will be interpolated (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

), 
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

recopy stable data: 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,4k}=y_{j,2k}\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 ; 
\layout Enumerate

Apply the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc tetradic scheme on even (stable) nodes: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,4k+1}=\frac{-7y_{j,2k-2}+105y_{j,2k}+35y_{j,2k+2}-5y_{j,2k+4}}{128};\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,4k+2}^{temporary}=\frac{-y_{j,2k-2}+9y_{j,2k}+9y_{j,2k+2}-y_{j,2k+4}}{128};\]

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,4k+3}=\frac{-5y_{j,2k-2}+35y_{j,2k}+105y_{j,2k+2}-7y_{j,2k+4}}{128}\, \forall k\in \Z ;\]

\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

Update midpoint (which then becomes stable): 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,4k+2}=(1-\alpha )y_{j+1,4k+2}^{temporary}+\alpha y_{j,2k+1};\]

\end_inset 


\layout Enumerate

Repeat with 
\begin_inset Formula $j\rightarrow j+1$
\end_inset 

 and using 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1}$
\end_inset 

 as initial data.
 
\end_deeper 
\layout Standard

This new algorithm is not a subdivision scheme in general and thus we need
 to propose a more general definition: stationary subdivision schemes (equation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{basicsubdivision}

\end_inset 

) can be generalized by the linear equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{m=1}^{M}\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{Mbk+m-1-l}^{(m)}y_{j,Mk+m-1}\label{hrgeneral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{(1)},...,\gamma ^{(M)}$
\end_inset 

 are constant arrays (independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

).
 It can be said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $b-$
\end_inset 

adic because the number of nodes is increasing by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset 

 with each iteration but because we have 
\begin_inset Formula $M>1$
\end_inset 

 arrays 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma $
\end_inset 

, the scheme is said to be a high resolution subdivision scheme.
 We say it is interpolatory if it satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,Mbk}=y_{j+1,Mk}$
\end_inset 

 and it is 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{l}^{(m)}=0$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $|l|>=MNb$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,...,M$
\end_inset 

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=M=2$
\end_inset 

 the general equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrgeneral}

\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-l}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k+1-l}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}.\label{N2highres}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It is interpolatory if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,4k}=y_{j+1,2k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{l}^{(m)}=0$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $|l|>=4N$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,2$
\end_inset 

.
 It should be noted that for an algorithm based on high resolution subdivision
 scheme to be interpolatory, the initialization step must be interpolatory
 (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,bk}=y_{j-1,k}$
\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

The interpolatory algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

 amounts to choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{(1)}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma ^{(2)}$
\end_inset 

 to be:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\gamma _{2k}^{(1)}=\gamma _{2k}^{DD4}+\alpha \left(\delta _{k,0}-\gamma _{k}^{DD2}\right),\,  & \gamma _{2k+1}^{(1)}=\gamma _{2k+1}^{DD4}\, \forall k\in \Z  & \label{N2highres_{1}}\\
\gamma _{-1}^{(2)}=\alpha ,\,  & \gamma _{k}^{(2)}=0\, otherwise & \label{N2highres_{2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 for some parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha \in \R $
\end_inset 

.
 Indeed, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma _{k}^{DD2}\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

, we can rewrite equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 for even and odd terms.
 Firstly, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $l=2s$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 even), we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
y_{j+1,2s} & =\sum _{k\in \Z } & \gamma _{4k-2s}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k+1-2s}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}\\
 & =\sum _{k\in \Z } & \left(\gamma _{4k-2s}^{DD4}-\alpha \gamma _{2k-s}^{DD2}+\alpha \delta _{4k,2s}\right)y_{j,2k}+\alpha \delta _{4k+2,l}y_{j,2k+1}\\
 & =\sum _{k\in \Z } & \left((1-\alpha )\gamma _{2k-s}^{DD2}+\alpha \delta _{2k,s}\right)y_{j,2k}+\delta _{2k+1,s}\alpha y_{j,2k+1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 so that when 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is even (
\begin_inset Formula $l=2s=4r$
\end_inset 

), we have the interpolatory condition 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,4r}=y_{j,2r}\label{hrsinterpole}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 otherwise, when 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is odd 
\begin_inset Formula $(l=2s=4r+2)$
\end_inset 


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,4r+2}=\alpha y_{j,2r+1}+(1-\alpha )\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}.\label{hrsricharson}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Secondly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset 

 is odd (
\begin_inset Formula $l=2s+1$
\end_inset 

), we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
y_{j+1,2s+1} & = & \sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2s-1}^{(1)}y_{j,2k}+\gamma _{4k-2s-1}^{(2)}y_{j,2k+1}\nonumber \\
 & = & \sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2s-1}^{DD4}y_{j,2k}.\label{hrswidguess}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 Equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsinterpole}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 can be used to describe the chosen high resolution schemes: while equation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsinterpole}

\end_inset 

 is the interpolatory condition, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 fills the placeholders with tetradic (coarse scale) interpolated values
 whereas equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

 combines the value stored in the placeholder with the newly available interpola
ted value (fine scale) given by the summation term which we recognize from
 the dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc interpolation.
\layout Standard

In the simplest case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =0$
\end_inset 

, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-l}^{DD4}y_{j,2k}.\label{N2highresalpha0}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =0\Rightarrow \gamma ^{(2)}=0$
\end_inset 

, we see that the placeholders (odd nodes) are effectively ignored.
 Indeed, we observe that this last equation discards odd nodes at each step:
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,l}$
\end_inset 

 depends only on even nodes (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

 ) and not at all on the odd nodes ( 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k+1}$
\end_inset 

).
 Hence, we can replace equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highresalpha0}

\end_inset 

 by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,2l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2l}^{DD4}y_{j,2k}\]

\end_inset 

 but because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma _{k}^{DD2}$
\end_inset 

 , this last equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,2l}=\gamma _{2k-l}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

 and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}_{j,k}=y_{j,2k}$
\end_inset 

 then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\widetilde{y}_{j+1,2l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-l}^{DD2}\widetilde{y}_{j,2k}\label{DD2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which we recognize as the cubic Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme and we have proved
 the next proposition.
\layout Proposition


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{propDesDuequiv}

\end_inset 

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =0$
\end_inset 

, the high resolution scheme given by algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

 (or equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_1}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_2}

\end_inset 

) is equivalent to the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc subdivision scheme.
 
\layout Section

Local properties
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point high resolution subdivision schemes are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

as local as
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point subdivision scheme: it is not surprising since interpolated values
 depend only on the closest 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset 

 nodes and we use a dyadic tree.
 As an example, consider any 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point dyadic high resolution scheme.
 Since the algorithm is linear, stationary and homogeneous, we can choose
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,0}=1$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,k}=0$
\end_inset 

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq 0$
\end_inset 

 to characterize locality.
 As an initialization step, apply any interpolatory 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-$
\end_inset 

point dyadic subdivision scheme: the farthest non-zero interpolated values
 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,\pm (2N-1)}$
\end_inset 

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm \xi _{0}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi _{0}=\frac{2N-1}{2}$
\end_inset 

.
 We then apply the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point high resolution subdivisions scheme itself treating the odd nodes
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,-(2N-1)},...,y_{1,2N-1}$
\end_inset 

 as placeholders, the farthest non-zero interpolated values will be at 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm \xi _{1}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi _{1}=\xi _{0}+\frac{2N-1}{2^{2}}$
\end_inset 

: in this respect, a high resolution subdivision scheme behaves just like
 subdivision schemes.
 Of course, these farthest values are not stable yet since they are located
 at odd nodes, but they will become stable on the next interation.
 By induction, the farthest non-zero interpolated values after 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

 interations is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi _{n}=\sum _{k=1}^{n}\frac{2N-1}{2^{k}}$
\end_inset 

 which converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $2N-1$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow \infty $
\end_inset 

 and hence, the support of the interpolated function has to be in 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-2N,2N-1]$
\end_inset 

.
 A similar argument could be made when 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq 2$
\end_inset 

 (non-dyadic case).
\layout Section

Reproduced polynomials
\layout Standard

Assume that for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}=p_{3}\left(x_{j,k}\right)\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 for some cubic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{3}$
\end_inset 

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point Deslauriers-Dubuc schemes reproduce cubic polynomials, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}=y_{j,2r+1}=p_{3}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 and thus equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,4r+2}=p_{3}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha $
\end_inset 

.
 Similarly, equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,2s+1}=p_{3}\left(x_{j+1,2s+1}\right)$
\end_inset 

.
 We can conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,k}=p_{3}\left(x_{j+1,k}\right)\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}=p_{3}\left(x_{j,k}\right)\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 and thus high resolution schemes defined by equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 reproduce cubic polynomials.
 As we have seen, for practical implementations of a high subdivision scheme,
 it is necessary to first apply a one-step subdivision scheme.
 This can be solved by a (one-step) dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc interpolation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y_{j,k}\right\} _{k}$
\end_inset 

 be some initial data.
 As a first step, we apply equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
y_{j+1,l}=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-l}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}\label{DD2_{2}}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 followed by algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $j+1$
\end_inset 

.
 By induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 using algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

, we get the following lemma.
\layout Lemma


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{lemmecubic}

\end_inset 

High resolution schemes given by algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

 (or equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_1}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_2}

\end_inset 

) using a one step interpolatory 4-point dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc interpolation
 (equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{DD2_2}

\end_inset 

) as an initialization step reproduce cubic polynomials and are interpolatory.
 
\layout Standard

We can also get a stronger result by choosing a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha $
\end_inset 

.
 We can write any polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{4}$
\end_inset 

as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{4}(x)=a_{4}x^{4}+p_{3}(x)$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{3}$
\end_inset 

 is some cubic polynomial.
 Suppose that for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}=p_{4}\left(x_{j,2k}\right)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j-1,k}=p_{4}\left(x_{j-1,k}\right)\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

.
 We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,4r+2}$
\end_inset 

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in \Z $
\end_inset 

 in terms of this initial data (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j-1}$
\end_inset 

) by substituting equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrswidguess}

\end_inset 

 into 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{hrsricharson}

\end_inset 

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
y_{j+1,4r+2} & = & \alpha y_{j,2r+1}+(1-\alpha )\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}\nonumber \\
 & = & \alpha \sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2r-1}^{DD4}y_{j-1,2k}+(1-\alpha )\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}y_{j,2k}.\label{upcomingrichardson}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j+1,4r+2}=p_{4}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)$
\end_inset 

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha $
\end_inset 

 and so we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k}=p_{4}\left(x_{j,2k}\right)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j-1,k}=p_{4}\left(x_{j-1,k}\right)$
\end_inset 

 into the two sums of this last equation.
 Because of the identities 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{-9}{2^{4j}} & = & \frac{-\left(x_{j,2r-2}\right)^{4}+9\left(x_{j,2r}\right)^{4}+9\left(x_{j,2r+2}\right)^{4}-\left(x_{j,2r+4}\right)^{4}}{128}-\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)^{4}\\
\frac{-105}{2^{4j}} & = & \frac{-7\left(x_{j,2r-4}\right)^{4}+105\left(x_{j,2r}\right)^{4}+35\left(x_{j,2r+4}\right)^{4}-5\left(x_{j,2r+8}\right)^{4}}{128}-\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)^{4}\\
 & = & \frac{-5\left(x_{j,2r-4}\right)^{4}+35\left(x_{j,2r}\right)^{4}+105\left(x_{j,2r+4}\right)^{4}-7\left(x_{j,2r+8}\right)^{4}}{128}-\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)^{4},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 we can compute both sums in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{upcomingrichardson}

\end_inset 

 explicitely: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2r-1}^{DD4}y_{j-1,2k} & = & p_{3}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)+a_{4}\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{4k-2r-1}^{DD4}\times \left(x_{j-1,2k}=x_{j,4k}\right)^{4}\\
 & = & p_{4}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)-\frac{105a_{4}}{2^{4j}}\label{105sur16}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 and
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}y_{j,2k} & = & p_{3}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)+a_{4}\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{2k-2r-1}^{DD2}\times \left(x_{j,2k}\right)^{4}\\
 & = & p_{4}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)-\frac{9a_{4}}{2^{4j}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 Hence, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =-3/32$
\end_inset 

 in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{upcomingrichardson}

\end_inset 

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula \[
y_{j+1,4r+2}=p_{4}\left(x_{j,2r+1}\right)-\frac{105\alpha +9(1-\alpha )}{2^{4j}}a_{4}=p_{4}\left(x_{j+1,4r+2}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 since for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =-3/32$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $105\alpha +9(1-\alpha )=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the scheme reproduces polynomials of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =-3/32$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

This last result assumes that we initialize the data so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,2k+1}=p_{4}\left(x_{j,2k+1}\right)-\frac{105a_{4}}{16\times 2^{4j}}$
