\layout Proposition


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{no4point}

\end_inset 

A 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point dyadic subdivision scheme cannot reproduce polynomials of degree 4.
 
\layout Proof

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{4}(x)=x(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)$
\end_inset 

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0,k}=P_{4}(k)$
\end_inset 

.
 All 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point subdivision schemes will interpolate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1,3}=0\neq P_{4}\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)=\frac{9}{16}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

By the proof of proposition 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{no4point}

\end_inset 

, we see that only subdivision schemes using 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset 

