\layout Standard

To study the regularity of high resolution schemes, it is convenient to
 rewrite formula 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 in terms of (trigonometric) polynomials.
 Given some data 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j,k}$
\end_inset 

, define 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j}(z)=\sum _{k\in \Z }y_{j,k}z^{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}(z)=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{k}^{DD2}z^{k}$
\end_inset 

, then the equation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc scheme (equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{DD2_2}

\end_inset 

), can be rewritten 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)=P_{2}(z)P^{j}(z^{2})$
\end_inset 

.
 Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{4}(z)=\sum _{k\in \Z }\gamma _{k}^{DD4}z^{k}$
\end_inset 

, then the tetradic subdivision scheme is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)=P_{4}(z)P^{j}(z^{2})$
\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{I}$
\end_inset 

t can be shown that we can rewrite the general equation for high resolution
 subdivision schemes as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P^{j+1}(z)=\sum _{i=1}^{M}\Phi _{i}(z)P^{j}\left(e^{2\pi i/b}z^{b}\right).\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{i}$
\end_inset 

 must be Laurent polynomials and similarly for dyadic schemes (
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

), 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P^{j+1}(z)=\Phi _{1}(z)P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\Phi _{2}(z)P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right).\]

\end_inset 

 The equation of symbols for the 
\begin_inset Formula $4-$
\end_inset 

point cubic high resolution sheme is (see equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 and algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

)
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
P^{j+1}(z) & = & \left\{ P_{4}\left(z\right)-\alpha P_{2}\left(z^{2}\right)+\alpha \right\} \left(\frac{P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)}{2}\right)+\alpha \left(\frac{P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)-P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)}{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \left\{ \frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)-\alpha P_{2}\left(z^{2}\right)}{2}+\alpha \right\} P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)-\alpha P_{2}\left(z^{2}\right)}{2}P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & \Gamma _{1}(z)P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\Gamma _{2}(z)P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right).\label{gammas}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma _{2k}^{DD4}=\gamma _{k}^{DD2}\, \forall k\in \Z $
\end_inset 

, we observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset 

 is not needed and everything can be written in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{4}$
\end_inset 

, indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{4}\left(z\right)-\alpha P_{2}\left(z^{2}\right)=\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)-P_{4}\left(-z\right)}{2}+(1-\alpha )\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)+P_{4}\left(-z\right)}{2}\]

\end_inset 

 and thus, the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{1}$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{2}$
\end_inset 

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\Gamma _{1}(z) & = & \Gamma _{2}(z)+\alpha \\
\Gamma _{2}(z) & = & \frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)-P_{4}\left(-z\right)}{4}+(1-\alpha )\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)+P_{4}\left(-z\right)}{4}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =0$
\end_inset 

 (Deslauriers-Dubuc case), 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{1}(z)=\Gamma _{2}(z)=\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)}{2}$
\end_inset 

 and equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula \[
P^{j+1}(z)=P_{4}\left(z\right)\left(\frac{P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)}{2}\right)\]

\end_inset 

 and it can be shown to be equivalent to the Deslauriers-Dubuc dyadic scheme
 by using the last equation for averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(-z)$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{P^{j+1}(z)+P^{j+1}(-z)}{2} & = & \left(\frac{P_{4}\left(z\right)-P_{4}\left(-z\right)}{2}\right)\left(\frac{P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)}{2}\right)\\
 & = & P_{2}\left(z^{2}\right)\left(\frac{P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)}{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 which can be used to prove that when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha =0$
\end_inset 

 the high resolution subdivision scheme becomes the dyadic Deslauriers-Dubuc
 scheme (proposition 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{propDesDuequiv}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Standard

In order to study the regularity and stability of the chosen high resolution
 schemes, we need to find corresponding schemes for the (forward) finite
 differences.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{j}=1/2^{j}$
\end_inset 

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula \[
D_{j,k}=\frac{dy_{j,k}}{dx_{j}}=2^{j}\left(y_{j,k+1}-y_{j,k}\right),\]

\end_inset 

 and define higher order finite differences recursively 
\begin_inset Formula \[
D_{j,k}^{n}=d^{(n)}y_{j,k}/\left(dx_{j}\right)^{n}=d\left(d^{(n-1)}y_{j,k}\right)/\left(dx_{j}\right)^{n}=2^{jn}\times d^{(n)}y_{j,k}.\]

\end_inset 

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{j,k}=D_{j,k}^{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}^{j}$
\end_inset 

 be the symbol for 
\begin_inset Formula $dy_{j,k}/dx_{j}$
\end_inset 

, then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
H_{1}^{j}(z) & = & \sum _{k\in \Z }2^{j}\left(y_{j,k+1}-y_{j,k}\right)z^{k}\\
 & = & \sum _{k\in \Z }2^{j}y_{j,k}z^{k-1}-\sum _{k\in \Z }2^{j}y_{j,k}z^{k}\\
 & = & 2^{j}(1/z-1)P^{j}(z)=2^{j}(1-z)P^{j}(z)/z,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)=z^{2}2^{j}H_{1}^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)/(1-z^{2})$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)=-z^{2}2^{j}H_{1}^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)/(1+z^{2})$
\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)=z2^{j+1}H_{1}^{j+1}(z)/(1-z)$
\end_inset 

.
 Substituting these three equations into 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{j+1}(z)=\Gamma _{1}(z)P^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\Gamma _{2}(z)P^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right)$
\end_inset 

 (equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{gammas}

\end_inset 

) gives
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{1}^{j+1}(z)=\frac{2z(1-z)}{(1-z^{2})}\Gamma _{1}(z)H_{1}^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)-\frac{2z(1-z)}{(1+z^{2})}\Gamma _{2}(z)H_{1}^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right).\label{notsogen}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Similarly, the higher order finite differences are given by
\begin_inset Formula \[
H_{n}^{j}(z)=\frac{2(1-z)}{z}H_{n-1}^{j}(z)=\left(\frac{2(1-z)}{z}\right)^{n}P^{j}(z)\]

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(z)=P(z)$
\end_inset 

 and it can be seen that they can be computed by (see derivation of equation
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{notsogen}

\end_inset 

 above) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{n}^{j+1}(z)=\left(\frac{2z}{1+z}\right)^{n}\Gamma _{1}(z)H_{n}^{j}\left(z^{2}\right)+\left(\frac{-2z(1-z)}{1+z^{2}}\right)^{n}\Gamma _{2}(z)H_{n}^{j}\left(-z^{2}\right).\label{genh}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is said to be the symbol of a high resolution subdivision scheme if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{1}(z)/(1+z)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{2}(z)/(1+z^{2})$
\end_inset 

 are Laurent polynomials.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{1}(z)/(1+z)^{n}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma _{2}(z)/(1+z^{2})^{n}$
\end_inset 

 are Laurent polynomial for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{n}=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset 

 because
\begin_inset Formula \[
P_{4}(z)=\frac{-\left(1+z\right)^{4}\left(1+z^{2}\right)^{4}\left(5z^{2}-12z+5\right)}{128z^{7}}.\]

\end_inset 

 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is the symbol of a high resolution subdivision scheme if 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Lemma

For high resolution subdivision schemes given by algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{4pointhrssalgo}

\end_inset 

 (or equations 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_1}

\end_inset 

, and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{N2highres_2}

\end_inset 

